<dl id="n25068d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25068d">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25068d"> 68(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> figblabber <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25068d"><li>FW 42.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n25068d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n25068d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25068d">MS BL 47472-220</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:079 <a name="bd5" href="../../ff/fdra/bda.htm#bd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/bd5.htm#n25068d">Draft: I.2&sect;2.5</a>/3.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> language, from the simple phrases of common life to the highest abstract terms, rests on the concrete. To &lsquo;apprehend&rsquo; a thing is to &lsquo;seize&rsquo; or &lsquo;lay hold&rsquo; of it; to &lsquo;possess&rsquo; a thing is to &lsquo;sit by&rsquo; or &lsquo;beset&rsquo; it. To call one man a &lsquo;sycophant&rsquo; is to borrow the term &lsquo;<mark>fig-blabber</mark>,&apos; applied by the Greeks to the informer against those who broke the Attic law prohibiting the export of figs; <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 55</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fig-blabber: a sycophant (literally, from the Greek root of that word). </mm> </dd></dl>
